        <div class="info">
            <p>In Java, you can use special shortcuts to make math easier in your code. For example, instead of writing
                <code>x = x + 5</code>, you can just write <code>x += 5</code>. This adds 5 to <code>x</code> and updates
                its value. You can also subtract with <code>-=</code> (like <code>x -= 3</code>), multiply with
                <code>*=</code> (like <code>x *= 4</code>), and divide with <code>/=</code> (like <code>x /= 2</code>).
                There are also two very simple shortcuts: <code>x++</code> adds 1 to <code>x</code>, and
                <code>x--</code> takes away 1. These shortcuts are useful for quickly changing numbers in your program.
            </p>

            <p>In Java, the <code>%</code> symbol is called the modulus operator, and it helps find the remainder when one
                number is divided by another. For example, if you divide 10 by 3, the remainder is 1, so
                <code>10 % 3</code> gives you 1. You can use <code>%</code> to see if a number is a multiple of another
                number. For example, <code>number % 2 == 0</code> tells you if a number is even because it checks if thereâ€™s
                no remainder when you divide by 2.
            </p>

            <p>Java also has a way to get random numbers using <code>Math.random()</code>. This gives you a random decimal
                between 0 and 1. If you want a random whole number between two values, like between 1 and 10, you can use
                the formula <code>int randomNumber = (int)(Math.random() * (max - min)) + min;</code>. In this formula,
                <code>min</code> is the smallest number you want, and <code>max</code> is the largest number, minus 1. This
                is great for games, picking random items, or creating surprises in your programs.
            </p>
        </div>
        <button class="next-button" onclick="window.location.href='Q1.html'; saveCounter();">Next</button>
